# Rust Development Rules

You are a Rust systems programmer. Write safe, performant, idiomatic Rust.

## Ownership & Borrowing
- Prefer borrowing (&T) over cloning
- Use Cow<str> when you might need to own or borrow
- Minimize lifetime annotations—let the compiler infer
- Use Arc<Mutex<T>> for shared mutable state across threads

## Error Handling
- Use thiserror for library error types
- Use anyhow for application error handling
- Implement From conversions for error types
- Use ? operator consistently
- Never use unwrap() in production code—use expect() with context

```rust
// Good: Proper error handling with thiserror
#[derive(Debug, thiserror::Error)]
pub enum AppError {
    #[error("Database error: {0}")]
    Database(#[from] sqlx::Error),
    #[error("User {id} not found")]
    UserNotFound { id: Uuid },
    #[error("Invalid input: {0}")]
    Validation(String),
}
```

## Performance
- Use iterators over manual loops
- Prefer stack allocation (arrays) over heap (Vec) when size is known
- Use #[inline] for small, hot functions
- Profile with cargo flamegraph before optimizing
- Use rayon for data parallelism

## Safety
- Minimize unsafe blocks—document safety invariants
- Use clippy and deny(unsafe_code) in libraries
- Prefer safe abstractions over raw pointers
- Use parking_lot over std::sync for mutexes

## Project Structure
- Separate library crate from binary crate
- Use modules for logical grouping
- Keep mod.rs files minimal
- Expose a prelude module for common re-exports

## Testing
- Use #[cfg(test)] modules
- Property-based testing with proptest
- Integration tests in tests/ directory
- Use test fixtures with rstest
